content: Hi, I’m Armaan Tobaccowalla. I’m a student at the University of Pennsylvania studying computer science. My hobbies include programming, swimming, and listening to music. I’m interested in the intersection of technology and business and love to apply technology in new ways.

title: Hello World

content: django-labs-accounts is a reusable Django app to automatically set up Penn Labs accounts on our Django backends. It consists of an OAuth2 client to communicate with Platform and a user backend to log in users using Platform’s accounts.
summary: A reusable Django app for Penn Labs accounts
title: django-labs-accounts

content: docker-shibboleth-sp-nginx is a docker image base for Shibboleth SP and nginx, it is based on Debian Buster (Slim). It is intended to be used as a base to easily create docker images with Shibboleth authentication. Platform is built using docker-shibboleth-sp-nginx.
summary: A docker image base for Shibboleth SP and nginx
title: docker-shibboleth-sp-nginx

content: docker-tox is a custom tox docker image for use within CircleCI. It is used within Penn Labs to test our PyPI packages in multiple Python environments before publishing them.
summary: A custom tox docker image for use within CircleCI
title: docker-tox

content: My connected home network (or Homelab) consists of 2 physical servers, a virtual-machine host (Proxmox) and a File server (FreeNAS). Proxmox runs over 25 virtual machines and containers. The Homelab provides various services such as a software firewall, a remote SSH access server, a reverse proxy with Lets Encrypt TLS certificates, a VPN server with certificate authentication, a wiki for internal documentation, a mail server to send external mail, and a home automation system. Some of the software using in my homelab is: FreeNAS, Gitlab, Grafana, InfluxDB, Jekyll, Mediawiki, MySQL, Nginx, OpenHAB, pfSense, Postfix, and Telegraf.
summary: An intranet to learn and make my life easier
title: Homelab

content: Penn Clubs is Penn Labs product to democratize information about clubs. It uses Penn Labs accounts to allow students at Penn to easily find information about clubs, their events, and applications. Penn Clubs also allows students to add themselves to clubs’ mailing lists and join clubs as members. It is built using a Django backend and a React frontend.
summary: A Penn Labs product to democratize
title: Penn Clubs

content: pfsense-to-influxdb is a metric exporter from pfSense, a software firewall, to InfluxDB, a time series database. pfsense-to-influxdb was built to allow monitoring of pfSense within Grafana, a popular dashboard for metrics.
title: pfsense-to-influxdb

content: Platform is a backend API for all of Penn Labs’ products. It is the brains of Penn Labs’ account system which allows users to login through the University of Pennsylvania’s SSO provider (Shibboleth). Platform also provides information to dynamically render our website.
summary: A backend API for all of Penn Labs' products
title: Platform

content: As part of the New Jersey Governor’s School in the Sciences, I helped design and build a speaker recognition utility that could identify the speaker of a specific keyword from a closed set of individuals. The program used machine learning and was 100% accurate in identifying individuals.
summary: A program to determine the speaker of a keyword
title: Speaker Recognition Utility

content: I made a collection of templates with Penn Labs’ suggested configuration for various types of projects. These templates include configuration for testing, building, and deploying projects. As well as suggested application defaults.
summary: A collection of templates for Penn Labs' products
title: Templates

content: I made an aggregate Wage Tracker for the US economy by reverse engineering a similar Goldman Sachs model. My model is built using the first principal component of five common wage indicators.
summary: An aggregate wage tracker for the US economy
title: Wage Tracker
